                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-217-off1243 t18260914-217-crimeloc1245"></join>. Mr. Moore is a <rs id="t18260914-217-viclabel1246" type="occupation">broker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-217-victim1243 t18260914-217-viclabel1246"></join>, and lives in Russell-street. On the 29th of August, between twelve and one o'clock, I saw Ruby in his shop, and Spencer standing right opposite; they were looking at each other - a third person stood against the post, at the corner of Drury-lane, four doors from Moore's. I saw Ruby come out of the shop, and Spencer crossed to him - the third one came half way to meet them; Ruby made a motion with his mouth, and they went away - one back to the post, and Spencer stopped in the road; they then all went to the post together; I went down Drury-lane, to a broker's-shop, and continued to watch them; I saw Ruby and Spencer go away - I then saw them come back, and give the other a looking-glass; he went on the other side of the way, and they kept on this side - I ran and told Moore, and we both went after them; a boy told us they were gone down Orange-court; I then saw Spencer, and then Ruby, came up. I had not seen them bring the glass out of the shop - it was a square glass.</p>
               <p>SAMUEL MOORE. I keep this shop. On the 29th of August I lost a looking-glass, which stood about the middle of the shop, on a table, to which it was tied. I have never seen it since.</p>
